        <h1 class="govuk-heading-l">User Guide Template</h1>
        <p class="govuk-body">Creating a user guide for your product or service is an important aspect as it will not only help your end users but also other developers that may come on to the project at a later date. It should be written as clearly as possible and help a user understand how to use your product or service. You should regularly review your guide to ensure that it is up to date with the latest updates you are rolling out.</p>
        <p class="govuk-body">To provide a consistent experience we have reused the technical documentation template provided by GDS.</p>
        <img src="/images/user-guide-template.png" class="image" style=""/>
        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Creating a new User Guide Documentation Repository</h2>
        <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">1. Creating a new repository</h3>
        <p class="govuk-body">To make this as easy as possible we have created a template repository from which you can quickly create new repositories which include all the files you need to get started.
        </p>
        <img src="/images/new-user-guide.png" class="image dss-image"/>
        <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">2. Hosting your user Guide Documentation site</h3>
        <p class="govuk-body">To make hosting as easy as possible we have used a Jekyll theme which allows the site to be hosted directly on GitHub. To configure GitHub pages hosting go to the repository settings and scroll down to the GitHub pages section and select the <b>Master</b> branch as the source for your GitHub pages site. Whenthis is done GitHub will handle building your site each time changes are made to files in the <b>Master</b> branch.</p>
